  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international guidelines established\n- Limited scope of financial institutions\n\n2. 1980s-1990s\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Enhanced customer due diligence rules\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n\n3. Post-9/11 Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n- Stricter international cooperation\n- Enhanced information sharing mechanisms\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n- Global sanctions frameworks\n\n5. Key Legislative Principles\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced record-keeping\n- Cross-border information exchange\n- Significant financial penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- AI and machine learning for detection\n- Automated transaction monitoring\n- Advanced risk assessment technologies\n\nThe legislation continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques and technological challenges.",
